<Project Sdk="Microsoft.NET.Sdk">

  <PropertyGroup>
    <TargetFramework>net8.0</TargetFramework>
    <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>
    <RootNamespace>FieldCure.Mcp.Rag</RootNamespace>
    <AssemblyName>fieldcure-mcp-rag</AssemblyName>
    <Nullable>enable</Nullable>
    <ImplicitUsings>enable</ImplicitUsings>

    <Version>2.4.3</Version>
    <PackageId>FieldCure.Mcp.Rag</PackageId>

    <Authors>Jong Hyun Kim</Authors>
    <Company>Fieldcure Co., Ltd.</Company>
    <Copyright>Copyright (c) 2026 Fieldcure Co., Ltd.</Copyright>
    <Description>MCP RAG server with hybrid BM25 + vector search and AI-powered chunk contextualization. Chunks documents, enriches chunks with AI-generated context and keywords, generates embeddings, and performs keyword (FTS5) and semantic (cosine similarity) search with Reciprocal Rank Fusion.</Description>
    <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>
    <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/fieldcure/fieldcure-mcp-rag</PackageProjectUrl>
    <RepositoryUrl>https://github.com/fieldcure/fieldcure-mcp-rag</RepositoryUrl>
    <RepositoryType>git</RepositoryType>
    <PackageTags>mcp;mcp-server;ai;dotnet;rag;embedding;vector-search;knowledge-base;bm25</PackageTags>
    <PackageReleaseNotes>v2.4.3: Two fixes for the "RAG looks ready but every start_reindex returns already_running forever" symptom that hit users when an indexing run was killed before its finalizer could clean up. (1) start_reindex was guarded by an in-file flag (queue entry's StartedAt) that survived an orchestrator-process kill (OOM, OS kill, segfault, parent serve termination), even though the engine-side SQLite lock was cleared. The two guards disagreed and the file-side guard kept blocking new requests indefinitely. v2.4.3 adds a stale-lock recovery sweep — IsOrchestratorAlive(basePath) checks the orchestrator.lock PID, RecoverStaleRunningEntries converts orphaned StartedAt entries into the failed-replace branch — invoked unconditionally when the orchestrator boots and conditionally when start_reindex / cancel_reindex are called without a live orchestrator owning the lock. force=true is intentionally not extended to bypass the lock guard — the recovery path covers every dead-orchestrator case, and forcing past a live orchestrator risks corrupting in-flight SQLite writes. (2) The IsLockStale PID-reuse defense parsed Z-suffixed ISO timestamps with default DateTime.TryParse, which returns Kind=Local and silently shifted the value by the host's local offset; on KST the diff was always ~32400 s and the 5-second skew tolerance flagged every live lock as stale. AdjustToUniversal | AssumeUniversal keeps both sides in UTC. Ten new tests cover the recovery primitives, IsLockStale TZ behavior, and the start_reindex / cancel_reindex tool surface; validated end-to-end by killing a real indexing orchestrator mid-whisper-transcription and confirming the next start_reindex auto-recovered to status="queued".</PackageReleaseNotes>
    <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>
    <PackageIcon>Logo.png</PackageIcon>

    <PackageType>McpServer</PackageType>
    <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>
    <ToolCommandName>fieldcure-mcp-rag</ToolCommandName>
  </PropertyGroup>

  <ItemGroup>
    <InternalsVisibleTo Include="FieldCure.Mcp.Rag.Tests" />
  </ItemGroup>

  <ItemGroup>
    <None Include="README.md" Pack="true" PackagePath="" />
    <None Include="Logo.png" Pack="true" PackagePath="" />
    <None Include=".mcp/server.json" Pack="true" PackagePath=".mcp/" />
  </ItemGroup>

  <ItemGroup>
    <PackageReference Include="ModelContextProtocol" Version="1.2.0" />
    <PackageReference Include="Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting" Version="8.*" />
    <PackageReference Include="Microsoft.Data.Sqlite" Version="8.*" />
    <PackageReference Include="System.Net.Http.Json" Version="8.*" />
    <PackageReference Include="FieldCure.DocumentParsers" Version="2.*" />
  </ItemGroup>

  <!-- OCR is Windows-only (Tesseract native binaries). On Linux/macOS the core
       PdfPig text-only parser is used; scanned-PDF pages yield empty text.
       Audio is Windows-only too (Whisper.net + NAudio Media Foundation): on
       non-Windows the audio extensions are unsupported and matching files
       silently return empty text from DocumentParserFactory.GetParser. -->
  <ItemGroup Condition="$([MSBuild]::IsOSPlatform('Windows'))">
    <PackageReference Include="FieldCure.DocumentParsers.Ocr" Version="1.*" />
    <PackageReference Include="FieldCure.DocumentParsers.Audio" Version="0.3.*" />

    <!-- Whisper.net CPU native runtime does not flow transitively into the
         packaged dotnet-tool output: PackAsTool strips runtimes/<rid>/native/
         from indirect dependencies, so without a direct PackageReference here
         the published tool would throw "Native Library not found in default
         paths" on the first audio indexing call.

         As of DocumentParsers.Audio v0.3 this is the *only* reason the
         reference is restated. The GPU runtimes (Whisper.net.Runtime.Cuda,
         Whisper.net.Runtime.Vulkan) are no longer in the dependency graph at
         all — Audio v0.3 dropped them and instead downloads them on first GPU
         use from https://github.com/fieldcure/fieldcure-whisper-runtimes
         (cached under %LOCALAPPDATA%\FieldCure\WhisperRuntimes\). The 250 MB
         nuget.org cap that drove the earlier CPU-only trade-off is no longer
         a constraint here: only the CPU runtime ever lands inside this nupkg. -->
    <PackageReference Include="Whisper.net.Runtime" Version="1.9.0" />
  </ItemGroup>

  <PropertyGroup Condition="$([MSBuild]::IsOSPlatform('Windows'))">
    <DefineConstants>$(DefineConstants);WINDOWS_OCR;WINDOWS_AUDIO</DefineConstants>
  </PropertyGroup>

  <ItemGroup Condition="!$([MSBuild]::IsOSPlatform('Windows'))">
    <Compile Remove="LazyOcrEngine.cs" />
    <Compile Remove="LazyAudioTranscriber.cs" />
  </ItemGroup>

</Project>
